<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img loading=3D"lazy" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"310" height=3D"61" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvi=
dhya.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/9615612.webp" alt=3D"n observations" cl=
ass=3D"wp-image-189970" style=3D"width:376px;height:auto"></figure></div>


<p>We need a value for theta which will maximize this likelihood function. =
To make our calculations easier we multiply the log on both sides. The func=
tion we get is also called the log-likelihood function or sum of the log co=
nditional probability</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img loading=3D"lazy" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"494" height=3D"64" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvi=
dhya.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/4487512.webp" alt=3D"log likelihood" cl=
ass=3D"wp-image-189971" style=3D"width:602px;height:auto"></figure></div>


<p>In machine learning, it is conventional to minimize a loss(error) functi=
on via gradient descent, rather than maximize an objective function via gra=
dient ascent. If we maximize this above function then we=E2=80=99ll have to=
 deal with gradient ascent to avoid this we take negative of this log so th=
at we use gradient descent. We=E2=80=99ll talk more about gradient descent =
in a later section and then you=E2=80=99ll have more clarity. Also, remembe=
r,</p>



<blockquote class=3D"wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout=
-flow">
<p><em><strong>max[log(x)] =3D min[-log(x)]</strong></em></p>
</blockquote>



<p>The negative of this function is our&nbsp;<em><strong>cost function</str=
ong></em>&nbsp;and what do we want with our cost function? That it should h=
ave a minimum value. It is common practice to minimize a cost function for =
optimization problems; therefore, we can invert the function so that we min=
imize the negative log-likelihood (NLL). So in logistic regression, our cos=
t function is:</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img loading=3D"lazy" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"513" height=3D"66" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvi=
dhya.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/8674112.webp" alt=3D"cost function" cla=
ss=3D"wp-image-189972" style=3D"width:583px;height:auto"></figure></div>


<p>Here y represents the actual class and log(<strong>=CF=83(</strong>=CE=
=B8^T*x^i<strong>) )&nbsp;</strong>is the probability of that class.</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>p(y) is the probability of 1.</li>



<li>1-p(y) is the probability of 0.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-let-s-see-what-will-be-the-graph-of-=
cost-function-when-y-1-and-y-0">Let=E2=80=99s see what will be the graph of=
 cost function when y=3D1 and y=3D0</h4>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"804" height=3D"249" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvidhya.com/w=
p-content/uploads/2024/08/7534219.webp" alt=3D"y=3D1 and y=3D0" class=3D"wp=
-image-189973"></figure></div>


<p>If we combine both the graphs, we will get a convex graph with only 1 lo=
cal minimum and now it=E2=80=99ll be easy to use gradient descent here:</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"930" height=3D"429" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvidhya.com/w=
p-content/uploads/2024/10/image-16.png" alt=3D"convex graph with only 1 loc=
al minimum and now it'll be easy to use gradient descent here" class=3D"wp-=
image-197362"></figure></div>


<p>The red line here represents the 1 class (y=3D1), the right term of cost=
 function will vanish. Now if the predicted probability is close to 1 then =
our loss will be less and when probability approaches 0, our loss function =
reaches infinity.</p>



<p>The black line represents 0 class (y=3D0), the left term will vanish in =
our cost function and if the predicted probability is close to 0 then our l=
oss function will be less but if our probability approaches 1 then our loss=
 function reaches infinity.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full is-resized"><img loading=3D"lazy" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"488" height=3D"57" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvi=
dhya.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/8787314.webp" alt=3D"cost theta" class=
=3D"wp-image-189974" style=3D"width:556px;height:auto"></figure></div>


<p>This cost function is also called log loss. It also ensures that as the =
probability of the correct answer is maximized, the probability of the inco=
rrect answer is minimized. Lower the value of this cost function higher wil=
l be the accuracy.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-gradient-descent-optimization">Gradi=
ent Descent Optimization</h2>



<p>In this section, we will try to understand how we can utilize&nbsp;<em>G=
radient Descent</em>&nbsp;to compute the minimum cost.</p>



<p>Gradient descent changes the value of our weights in such a way that it =
always converges to minimum point or we can also say that, it aims at findi=
ng the optimal weights which minimize the loss function of our model. It is=
 an iterative method that finds the minimum of a function by figuring out t=
he slope at a random point and then moving in the opposite direction.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"872" height=3D"473" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvidhya.com/w=
p-content/uploads/2024/10/image-351.webp" alt=3D"Plot of a convex cost func=
tion versus weight illustrating gradient descent: shows an initial weight p=
oint with its gradient vector and successive small steps descending the cur=
ve toward the minimum cost." class=3D"wp-image-197359"></figure></div>


<p>At first gradient descent takes a random value of our parameters from ou=
r function. Now we need an algorithm that will tell us whether at the next =
iteration we should move left or right to reach the minimum point. The grad=
ient descent algorithm finds the slope of the loss function at that particu=
lar point and then in the next iteration, it moves in the opposite directio=
n to reach the minima. Since we have a convex graph now we don=E2=80=99t ne=
ed to worry about local minima. A convex curve will always have only 1 mini=
ma.</p>



<p>We can summarize the <a href=3D"https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/202=
0/10/how-does-the-gradient-descent-algorithm-work-in-machine-learning/" tar=
get=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer">gradient descent algorithm</a> a=
s:</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"261" height=3D"75" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvidhya.com/wp=
-content/uploads/2024/08/5064017.webp" alt=3D"gradient descent algorithm" c=
lass=3D"wp-image-189975"></figure></div>


<p>Here&nbsp;alpha&nbsp;is known as the learning rate. It determines the st=
ep size at each iteration while moving towards the minimum point. Usually, =
a lower value of&nbsp;<em>=E2=80=9Calpha=E2=80=9D&nbsp;</em>is preferred, b=
ecause if the learning rate is a big number then we may miss the minimum po=
int and keep on oscillating in the convex curve.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-full"><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"767" height=3D"193" src=3D"https://cdn.analyticsvidhya.com/w=
p-content/uploads/2024/10/image-17.png" alt=3D"" class=3D"wp-image-197366">=
</figure></div>


<p>Now the question is what is this derivative of cost function? How do we =
do this? Don=E2=80=99t worry, In the next section we=E2=80=99ll see how we =
can derive this cost function w.r.t our parameters.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" id=3D"h-derivation-of-cost-function">Derivat=
ion of Cost Function</h2>



<p>Before we derive our cost function we=E2=80=99ll first find a derivative=
